Because i in the Fortran loop is (Java's i +1). So Java's i is (Fortran's loop i -1). So nglist stores Java's i values, which are (Fortran loop i -1). This is a bit tricky. Let's see:

Java code:

for (int i = 0; i < N-1; ++i) {
    if (map.get(i) > map.get(i+1)) {
        nglist.add(i);
    }
}

But in Fortran, the map.get(i) is pos(i+1)
